But when once Conſtantine the Great appear'd, enabled with the Riches and Authority of Empire, he bravely redreſſed all theſe horrid and inhuman practiſes,Euſeb. Hiſt. Lib. 10.
                and erected many ſtructures for to entertain and refreſh the ſons and daughters of pitty and compaſſion. This excellent example Julian the Apoſtate could not but applaud and imitate, as may be ſeen by his Letters ſent to the Proconſuls and Cities of Aſia, perſwading them to follow the examples of Chriſtians in this matter;


and though he reigned alone ſcarce two years, yet he left many monuments of Charity behind him.

